## Preface: Why This Book Exists

There is a war of words happening right now, and it is being fought with the wrong weapons.

On one side, you have people who insist that merit is all that matters — that the best person for the job should always get the job, full stop, and that any consideration of diversity is a form of discrimination dressed in progressive clothing. On the other side, you have people who argue that representation is a moral imperative, that historical injustice must be corrected through intentional inclusion, and that questioning diversity initiatives is tantamount to bigotry.

Both sides are wrong. Not morally wrong — though they may be that too — but technically wrong. Scientifically wrong. Wrong in the way that a physicist is wrong when they ignore friction, or an engineer is wrong when they optimize for a single variable in a multi-constraint system.

This book is not a political manifesto. It is not an attempt to validate one tribe or defeat another. It is an attempt to do something more difficult and more useful: to take a debate that has been conducted entirely in the language of ideology and translate it into the language of science.

The question we are really asking is not "who deserves the job?" The question is this: how do you build a system — a team, an organization, a crew, a civilization — that performs well under uncertainty, adapts to complex and unpredictable challenges, and does not collapse under its own rigidity? That is an engineering question. And like all engineering questions, it has answers that are better or worse, more or less rigorous, more or less honest.

Before a single algorithm is tuned or a single astronaut is selected, someone makes a decision about who should be in the room. That decision is the most important and least examined step in the entire process. This book is about that decision — what it means to get it right, what the science says, and what a framework for getting it right actually looks like.

We are going to try to be honest.

