### Chapter 6: The Competence Floor — The Line That Cannot Be Crossed

Here we must be direct, because the strongest legitimate critique of diversity initiatives is not wrong. It just applies to the wrong model.

The critique goes like this: if you optimize for diversity, you may end up selecting people who cannot do the job at the required level. In a hospital, this means patients die. In a cockpit, this means passengers die. In a nuclear facility or a spacecraft, this means everyone dies. No amount of cognitive diversity, no amount of expanded problem-solving repertoire, compensates for a team member who cannot perform the core technical function the mission requires.

This is correct. And it is why the model developed in this book builds on a foundation that the pure-diversity camp has often failed to articulate with sufficient clarity: the Competence Floor.

Formally, we define a Hard-Constraint Threshold θ as the minimum functional competence required for a given role in a given mission context. This threshold is not a social construct. It is a technical specification. It is defined by the mission requirements, not by the preferences of the selectors. It is non-negotiable, non-adjustable, and non-compensable by other team properties.

Below θ, an individual is not eligible for selection, regardless of any other attributes they possess. No amount of cognitive diversity, personality complementarity, or cultural breadth compensates for the inability to perform the core technical function. A surgeon who cannot complete the operation. A pilot who cannot fly the plane. An AI engineer who does not understand the mathematics of the system they are building. These are not diversity failures. They are competence failures, and the selection system must prevent them absolutely.

The Competence Floor is the answer to the MEI camp's most legitimate concern. It says, explicitly and formally: yes, there is a baseline below which selection criteria other than technical competence are irrelevant. We agree. We are drawing that line. We are making it hard.

But — and this is the move the MEI camp fails to make — once the Competence Floor is established and enforced, the optimization problem does not end. It begins. Above θ, the question is no longer "is this person good enough?" The question becomes "what combination of people above the floor produces the most capable, most robust, most adaptive team for the actual challenges this mission will face?"

And the answer to that question is not "the people with the highest individual scores." The mathematics of collective problem-solving, which we develop formally in the appendix, demonstrate that above a functional competence threshold, the marginal return on additional individual competence is lower than the marginal return on cognitive diversity. The best team is not composed of the ten highest-scoring individuals from a single cognitive mold. It is composed of the best-complementary individuals who all exceed the floor and whose collective repertoire covers the maximum possible surface area of the relevant problem space.

This is not politics. It is optimization theory.

