### Chapter 8: The Hidden Costs of Homogeneity

When an organization consistently selects for the same profile — the same educational background, the same problem-solving style, the same cultural assumptions, the same definition of what constitutes a good answer — it produces cognitive homogeneity.

Cognitive homogeneity is comfortable. Homogeneous teams communicate easily, agree quickly, and project high confidence. They are efficient in the short run. They are also brittle.

A homogeneous team exploring a solution space is like a search algorithm with very high exploitation and very low exploration. It is very good at optimizing within a known landscape. It is very bad at discovering that the landscape has changed, or that there is a different landscape entirely that would yield better results.

Scott Page, one of the most rigorous researchers on this question, has formalized this intuition in what he calls the Diversity Prediction Theorem: when a group of people make predictions about an uncertain outcome, the collective error of the group is equal to the average individual error minus the diversity of the group's predictions. This is not a metaphor. It is a mathematical identity. It means that, holding average individual ability constant, a more diverse group will always make more accurate collective predictions than a less diverse one.

Page also identifies what he calls the No Test Exists rule: no test applied to individuals will be guaranteed to produce the most cognitively diverse group. You cannot find the best team by finding the best individuals, because "best" is a relational property that depends on who else is on the team.

These are not arguments against excellence. They are arguments about what excellence means at the system level, as opposed to the individual level.

