## Part IV: The Diversity Evidence

### Chapter 9: What the Research Actually Shows

We owe it to the reader to be honest about the empirical landscape, which is more complicated than either side of the public debate acknowledges.

The evidence for diversity benefits is real, but it is conditional. A major review published in the *American Business Law Journal* in 2025 found that systematic meta-analyses show little evidence of a significant positive effect of demographic diversity on firm financial performance when studies are evaluated for methodological quality. Advocacy organizations and consultancies have selectively cited supportive research while ignoring contrary findings. The popular claim that diverse companies are significantly more profitable than less diverse ones has been challenged on methodological grounds.

This does not mean diversity doesn't matter. It means that demographic diversity — diversity of surface characteristics — does not automatically translate into the kind of cognitive diversity that produces performance gains. The relationship is mediated. Identity diversity produces cognitive diversity only under specific conditions, and cognitive diversity produces performance gains only on specific types of tasks.

The conditions under which diversity helps are now reasonably well established. The task must be genuinely complex, non-routine, and require the integration of multiple knowledge domains. The team must operate in an environment of psychological safety. The diversity must be complementary rather than merely different. And the team must have sufficient time and structural support to integrate. These conditions do not arise spontaneously. They must be engineered.

