### Chapter 15: The Formal Model

We can now state the core relationships with the precision they require. The full mathematical development is in the Appendix. Here we describe the architecture of the model and its implications.

Each candidate i is characterized by a capability vector with four components. The first is a Competence scalar C_i in the range zero to one, representing mastery of core technical requirements. The second is a Cognitive Repertoire R_i, representing the subset of the total relevant problem space that the individual can address — the collection of tools, heuristics, mental models, and knowledge structures they bring. The third is a Coordination Coefficient K_i, representing the individual's ability to synchronize their output with others. The fourth is a Personality Profile P_i in a multi-dimensional trait space, where specific clusters correlate with stability and adaptive capacity under stress.

The Hard-Constraint Floor θ establishes the non-negotiable minimum. A candidate is only eligible for selection if their Competence scalar C_i meets or exceeds θ. This threshold is defined by the mission's minimum safety requirements and is not adjustable by team composition considerations.

At the team level, the Cognitive Coverage of team T is the union of all individual repertoires — the total surface area of the team's collective problem-solving capability. The Blind Spot of the team is the complement of its coverage relative to the full mission requirements: the portion of the problem space that no team member can address. High-performing teams minimize their Blind Spot through complementary rather than redundant repertoires.

The Effective Performance of the team is a function of its Cognitive Coverage and its Coordination Entropy — the communication cost of integrating diverse cognitive frameworks. When Coordination Entropy is high and unmanaged, it absorbs the performance gains of diversity. When it is managed through Protocol Engineering, the Effective Performance captures the full benefit of cognitive breadth.

The Robustness Index measures the team's performance not at a single anticipated operating point but across the full distribution of possible mission environments, including those outside the initial design specification. A team with a high Robustness Index is a Swiss Army Team: one that performs acceptably across a wide range of conditions rather than optimally at a single one.

The Integration Mandate — the central theorem of this framework — states that for any sufficiently complex and novel task, there exists a level of cognitive diversity such that the Robustness Index of a diverse team exceeds that of a more homogeneous team of higher average individual competence, provided that the Coordination Entropy is managed below a critical threshold. This is the formal expression of the book's central thesis: diversity is not in tension with merit at the system level. Above the Competence Floor, it is a component of it.

