## Part VI: Applications in Critical Systems

### Chapter 16: Artificial Intelligence — Building Minds With Blind Spots

The teams that build artificial intelligence systems are, at this historical moment, among the most consequential human configurations on Earth. The systems they produce will affect billions of people across every domain of human activity. The assumptions embedded in those systems, the blind spots of their designers, the values implicit in their objective functions — all of these will propagate at scale and at speed into the world.

This makes the composition of AI development teams not merely an organizational question but a civilizational one.

The parallel to the team design problem developed throughout this book is exact. AI systems face a multi-objective optimization challenge: they must be capable, safe, robust to novel conditions, and aligned with a broad range of human values and needs. The teams that build them face an analogous challenge at the organizational level.

Cognitive homogeneity in AI teams produces systems that are excellent at the problems their designers anticipated and blind to the problems they did not. The history of AI safety failures is largely a history of blind spots — not of malice, not of incompetence, but of teams that were collectively unable to see what their systems would do in conditions they had not imagined. A system trained on data generated by a narrow slice of humanity will perform well for that slice and poorly for everyone else. A system designed by a team with a shared definition of what constitutes a desirable outcome will optimize for that definition and systematically fail to serve populations whose values differ.

This is not an argument for including people with lower technical ability in AI development teams. It is an argument for including people whose technical ability is high and whose problem framing, value assumptions, and experiential backgrounds are different. The most technically sophisticated AI safety failures — the ones that will matter most at civilizational scale — are not failures of mathematical competence. They are failures of imagination. They are failures to ask the right questions, to anticipate the right edge cases, to recognize when an objective function is subtly misspecified in ways that will become catastrophic at scale.

The multi-objective alignment problem in AI is formally isomorphic to the team design problem we have been studying. Recent research from the AI safety community has found that optimizing for a single objective — helpfulness, harmlessness, or honesty alone — reliably produces systems that are poorly calibrated on the others. The solution involves explicitly multi-objective reward frameworks, Pareto-optimal training strategies, and regular red-teaming by evaluators who do not share the assumptions of the system's designers.

The Adversarial Merit Evaluation framework proposed in Chapter 7 maps directly onto the red-teaming practices now recognized as essential in frontier AI development. A team that can only find the problems it was looking for is a team that will miss the problems that matter most. Selecting for the ability to generate orthogonal information — to see what the current system cannot see — is the same requirement whether the system being built is an AI model or a Mars crew.

The Diversity Buffer concept applies with full force to AI development timelines, which span years and encounter radically changing deployment contexts. An AI development team optimized for the capabilities and threat models of 2024 will be poorly positioned for the challenges of 2027, just as a Mars crew optimized for the departure phase is poorly positioned for the surface operations phase. Maintaining cognitive variance as an insurance policy against the rapid evolution of the problem space is not a compromise with technical excellence. It is a technical requirement.

